0 'OLC MSGDB'~
Every message going through char_xxx or act_xxx to player is
translated on-the-fly using msgdb facilities.
Additional functionality is available in act_xxx functions:
$cn{{text} - case number ``n'' of ``text''
$gx{{text} - ``x'' gender of ``text'', where ``x'' is:
            c - sex of ch
            v - sex of vch
            t - sex of player the message is being printed to
 
Examples:
1) msgdb contains the following message:
[eng] [$n drinks $T from $p.]
[rus] [$n  $c3{{$T}  $c1{{$p}.]
 
cases database of language "rus" (russian) contains the following
forms:
Name: []
Lang: [rus]
Type: [case]
Base: []
Form: [3] [-]
 
Name: []
Lang: [rus]
Type: [case]
Base: []
Form: [1] [-a]
 
and object has name 'fountain ' and short descr
[eng] fountain
[rus] 

and the liquid in object is "water".
 
When the player (fjoe) drinks from that object ("drink fount") other
players in his room will see:
"fjoe drinks water from the fountain." or "fjoe    ."
depending on their language (set by command "lang").
 
$gx{{..} and $cn{{...} calls can be nested. For example in the phrase
"        $c4{{$gc{{}}
 " the word "" will be taken in the gender form
depending on the sex of ch and then in the case form 4.
 
Forms can be created/edited with OLC via "create/edit form" commands.
See "help 'OLC FORMS INTRO"' for more info.
 
~
